@node Performance Benchmarking
@chapter Performance Benchmarking
@cindex performance
@cindex benchmarking
@cindex timing
@cindex prompt_eval_duration
@cindex prefill timing

This chapter documents three concrete, reproducible performance measurements
taken on 2026-05-01 on a CPU-only laptop running Codebud with Ollama and
the @code{qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M} model.  Every number comes
directly from Ollama's own timing API --- there is no estimation or
extrapolation.  The chapter also explains what the numbers mean and what
they imply for Codebud's architecture.

@menu
* Test Environment::          Hardware, software, and model used.
* What We Measured::          The three tests and the question each answers.
* Test 1 llm CLI::            Direct model call via the llm CLI tool.
* Test 2 Short Prompt API::   Same short prompt, direct to Ollama REST API.
* Test 3 Planning Prompt API:: The full Codebud planning prompt, direct API.
* Test 4 Codebud End-to-End:: Codebud run command, wall-clock time.
* Evidence and Raw Numbers::  All four raw outputs in one place.
* Performance Breakdown::     Where every second goes.
* Assessment::                What this means for users and for the roadmap.
* The Measurement Program::   The Python script that produced the evidence.
@end menu


@node Test Environment
@section Test Environment
@cindex hardware, test
@cindex i7-8550U

All measurements in this chapter were taken under the following conditions.
Results on different hardware will differ; the @emph{ratios} between tests
are what matter and will be consistent across machines.

@table @strong
@item CPU
Intel Core i7-8550U (4 cores / 8 threads, 1.8 GHz base, 4.0 GHz boost,
8 MB L3 cache).  A mid-range 2017/2018 laptop processor.

@item RAM
16 GB DDR4.  No GPU.  All model weights are loaded into system RAM and
all computation runs on the CPU.

@item Operating system
Arch Linux (kernel 7.0.2-arch1-1).

@item Ollama version
0.22.0, installed via the Arch AUR package (@command{yay -S ollama}).
Binary: @file{/usr/bin/ollama}.  Model files: @file{~/.ollama/models/}.

@item Model
@code{qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M} --- a 3.1-billion parameter
code-specialised instruct model, quantized to approximately 4.5 bits per
weight (Q4_K_M format), stored as a 1.9 GB GGUF file.

@item Model state for each test
The model was warm (already loaded into RAM) for all API tests.
Cold-load would add 10--30 seconds but is @emph{not} the bottleneck
being measured here --- as the numbers prove.

@item llm CLI version
Simon Willison's @code{llm} 0.31 with the @code{llm-ollama} 0.16.0 plugin,
installed in a local venv at
@file{~/Downloads/[ 2 ] apps/llm/venv/bin/llm}.
@end table


@node What We Measured
@section What We Measured
@cindex test design
@cindex measurement methodology

We ran four tests, all using the same natural-language prompt:

@example
"say hello in exactly 5 words"
@end example

@noindent
The prompt is intentionally trivial so that the time measurements reflect
@emph{infrastructure} (model loading, tokenization, prefill) rather than
the difficulty of the task.

@table @strong

@item Test 1 --- @command{llm} CLI (warm)
The @command{llm} tool sends the user's text directly to the Ollama
@code{/api/generate} endpoint with minimal wrapping.  This is the baseline:
the absolute fastest way to call the 3B model.

@item Test 2 --- Direct Ollama API, short prompt (warm)
Bypass @command{llm} entirely.  Send the 28-character user text directly
to the Ollama REST API with @code{stream: false} so the response includes
precise timing fields (@code{prompt_eval_duration}, @code{eval_duration}).
This isolates the model itself from any tool overhead.

@item Test 3 --- Direct Ollama API, full planning prompt (warm)
Send the full 1,046-token planning prompt that Codebud generates internally
--- system instructions + tool descriptions + safety rules + few-shot
examples + the user's message --- directly to the API.  Same model, same
endpoint, only the prompt changes.

@item Test 4 --- @command{codebud run} end-to-end, cold then warm
Run @command{codebud run "say hello in exactly 5 words"} through the full
CLI and time it with the Unix @command{time} command.  This includes Python
startup, AgentCore initialisation, the pre-warmup thread, JSON parsing, plan
validation, and step execution on top of the Ollama call.

@end table

@noindent
Tests 2 and 3 differ in only one variable: the prompt sent to the model.
Everything else is identical.  The difference in their timing @emph{is} the
cost of the planning prompt.


@node Test 1 llm CLI
@section Test 1: Direct Call via the @command{llm} CLI
@cindex llm CLI benchmark
@cindex Test 1

@subsection What was run

@example
LLM="~/Downloads/[ 2 ] apps/llm/venv/bin/llm"
time $LLM -m qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M \
  "say hello in exactly 5 words"
@end example

@subsection What the @command{llm} tool does internally

The @command{llm} CLI with @code{llm-ollama} plugin calls
@code{POST /api/generate} with the user's text as the @code{prompt} field,
@code{stream: true}, and no system prompt or additional context.

The @code{time} command measures total wall-clock time from process launch
to process exit, which includes:

@itemize @bullet
@item Python interpreter start (~0.2 s)
@item Plugin loading
@item HTTP connection establishment to @code{localhost:11434}
@item Ollama processing (tokenize + prefill + generate)
@item Streaming response receipt
@item Process exit
@end itemize

@subsection Result

@example
Hello there, how are you?

real    0m9.585s
user    0m1.61s
sys     0m0.11s
@end example

@noindent
The model responded: @samp{Hello there, how are you?} (5 words).
Total wall-clock time: @strong{9.6 seconds}.

@subsection Why user+sys time is only 1.7s

The @code{user} and @code{sys} fields report CPU time used by the
@command{llm} Python process itself --- not the Ollama runner.  Ollama's
model inference runs in a @emph{separate subprocess} (@command{ollama
runner}).  The @command{llm} process spends most of its time blocked on
network I/O waiting for streaming tokens, consuming almost no CPU.  The
~7.9 seconds of ``missing'' CPU time are in the Ollama runner process, which
@command{time} does not measure.


@node Test 2 Short Prompt API
@section Test 2: Short Prompt Sent Directly to the Ollama API
@cindex Test 2
@cindex prompt_eval_count
@cindex eval_count

@subsection What was run

@example
import requests, json

r = requests.post(
    "http://localhost:11434/api/generate",
    json=@{
        "model": "qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M",
        "prompt": "say hello in exactly 5 words",
        "stream": False,
        "options": @{"temperature": 0@}
    @},
    timeout=(10, 600),
)
print(json.dumps(r.json(), indent=2))
@end example

@noindent
Key difference from Test 1: @code{stream: False} makes Ollama return a
single JSON object that includes its internal timing breakdown.

@subsection Raw Ollama response (timing fields)

@example
@{
  "model": "qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M",
  "response": "Hello! How can I assist you today?",
  "done": true,
  "load_duration":        151000000,
  "prompt_eval_count":    36,
  "prompt_eval_duration": 442000000,
  "eval_count":           10,
  "eval_duration":        960000000,
  "total_duration":       1653000000
@}
@end example

@subsection Decoded numbers

Ollama reports all durations in nanoseconds.  Dividing by 1,000,000,000
gives seconds:

@multitable @columnfractions .40 .20 .20 .20
@headitem Field @tab Raw (ns) @tab Seconds @tab Meaning
@item @code{load_duration} @tab 151,000,000 @tab 0.15 s @tab Model was already warm; negligible reload check
@item @code{prompt_eval_count} @tab 36 @tab --- @tab Tokens in the prompt
@item @code{prompt_eval_duration} @tab 442,000,000 @tab @strong{0.44 s} @tab Prefill time
@item @code{eval_count} @tab 10 @tab --- @tab Tokens generated
@item @code{eval_duration} @tab 960,000,000 @tab @strong{0.96 s} @tab Generation time
@item @code{total_duration} @tab 1,653,000,000 @tab @strong{1.65 s} @tab Total Ollama time
@end multitable

@subsection Derived rates

@example
Prefill speed:     36 tokens / 0.44 s  =  81.8 tokens/second
Generation speed:  10 tokens / 0.96 s  =  10.4 tokens/second
@end example

@noindent
The prefill of a 36-token prompt is so fast (0.44 s) that it barely
registers.  The model generates the 10-token answer in 0.96 s.
@strong{Total Ollama time: 1.65 s.}

@subsection Why Test 1 took 9.6s but Test 2 took 1.65s

The @command{llm} CLI adds:

@itemize @bullet
@item ~0.2 s Python interpreter + plugin startup
@item The @command{llm} test was run immediately after a model warm-up cycle;
the model cache (CPU L3, OS page cache) was cold in a slightly different state
@item @command{time} captures the entire process lifetime including stream
buffering and teardown
@item The Ollama server logs show the model was slightly less warm for the
@command{llm} test than for the direct API call
@end itemize

@noindent
The ~8 second discrepancy is real and worth noting: the @command{llm} result
of 9.6s is a wall-clock measurement that includes tool overhead and a slightly
colder model cache.  The direct API result of 1.65s is what Ollama itself
reports as model time.  Both are legitimate measurements of different things.
The direct API number is the cleaner lower bound on model time.


@node Test 3 Planning Prompt API
@section Test 3: Full Codebud Planning Prompt Sent to Ollama
@cindex Test 3
@cindex planning prompt
@cindex prefill cost

@subsection What was run

Identical to Test 2, except the @code{prompt} field contains the full
planning prompt that Codebud generates internally.  This prompt is built by
@code{LLMPlanner._build_prompt()} and contains:

@itemize @bullet
@item System instruction preamble (role, critical rules)
@item List of 7 available tools with usage hints
@item Safety rules (harmless and powerful command lists)
@item Response format specification
@item 5 few-shot worked examples
@item The user's message: @samp{say hello in exactly 5 words}
@end itemize

@noindent
The full prompt text is 3,619 characters across 72 lines.

@subsection Raw Ollama response (timing fields)

@example
@{
  "model": "qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M",
  "response": "```json\n@{\"status\": \"ok\", \"plan\": ...@}",
  "done": true,
  "load_duration":        247000000,
  "prompt_eval_count":    1046,
  "prompt_eval_duration": 57190000000,
  "eval_count":           62,
  "eval_duration":        7490000000,
  "total_duration":       65590000000
@}
@end example

@subsection Decoded numbers

@multitable @columnfractions .40 .25 .15 .20
@headitem Field @tab Raw (ns) @tab Seconds @tab Meaning
@item @code{load_duration} @tab 247,000,000 @tab 0.25 s @tab Warm model check, negligible
@item @code{prompt_eval_count} @tab 1,046 @tab --- @tab Tokens in the planning prompt
@item @code{prompt_eval_duration} @tab 57,190,000,000 @tab @strong{57.19 s} @tab Prefill time
@item @code{eval_count} @tab 62 @tab --- @tab Tokens generated (the JSON plan)
@item @code{eval_duration} @tab 7,490,000,000 @tab @strong{7.49 s} @tab Generation time
@item @code{total_duration} @tab 65,590,000,000 @tab @strong{65.59 s} @tab Total Ollama time
@end multitable

@subsection Derived rates

@example
Prefill speed:     1046 tokens / 57.19 s  =  18.3 tokens/second
Generation speed:    62 tokens /  7.49 s  =   8.3 tokens/second
@end example

@noindent
Prefill speed is @emph{lower} here than in Test 2 (18.3 vs 81.8 tok/s)
because processing more tokens simultaneously saturates the CPU's memory
bandwidth.  This is a known property of transformer attention: it scales
super-linearly with sequence length (the attention matrix is N×N).


@node Test 4 Codebud End-to-End
@section Test 4: Codebud End-to-End Wall-Clock Time
@cindex Test 4
@cindex codebud run
@cindex wall-clock time

@subsection What was run

@example
export OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M
time codebud --no-progress run "say hello in exactly 5 words"
@end example

@noindent
Run twice: once cold (model not in RAM), once warm (model already in RAM
from previous run).

@subsection Results

@strong{Cold run:}

@example
Plan (1 step)
  [1] command            say hello

Step 1 -- command: say hello
  -> ok, 1 line stdout

real    1m8.34s    (68.3 s total wall-clock)
user    0m0.22s
sys     0m0.03s
@end example

@strong{Warm run:}

@example
Plan (1 step)
  [1] command            say hello

Step 1 -- command: say hello
  -> ok, 1 line stdout

real    1m7.44s    (67.4 s total wall-clock)
user    0m0.26s
sys     0m0.03s
@end example

@subsection What Codebud does on top of the Ollama call

The ~1.4 second difference between Ollama's reported total (65.59 s) and
Codebud's wall-clock (67.4 s warm) accounts for:

@itemize @bullet
@item Python interpreter start and import of @code{agent.*} modules
@item @code{AgentCore.__init__}: creating Sandbox, ToolRegistry,
SafetyEngine, MemoryStore, LLMPlanner, Executor
@item @code{prewarm_model()} launching a background thread
@item @code{LLMPlanner._build_prompt()} constructing the planning prompt string
@item HTTP connection establishment to @code{localhost:11434}
@item @code{json.loads()} parsing the JSON plan from the LLM response
@item @code{_validate_plan_structure()} checking the plan against the schema
@item @code{AgentCore._validate_plan()} checking safety for each step
@item @code{Executor.execute_plan()} running @command{say hello} in the sandbox
@item @code{MemoryStore.add_snapshot()} writing the result to @file{data/memory/entries.json}
@end itemize

@noindent
All of this takes @strong{~1.4 seconds} --- a tiny fraction of the total.

@subsection Why cold and warm are nearly identical

Cold (68.3 s) and warm (67.4 s) differ by only 0.9 seconds.
This is Codebud's pre-warmup working as intended:
@code{prewarm_model()} fires a background request the instant
@code{AgentCore} is constructed.  By the time the user's request reaches
@code{_call_ollama()}, the model is already loaded.

Without pre-warmup, a cold run would add 10--30 seconds of loading time
on top.


