@node Performance Breakdown
@section Performance Breakdown: Where Every Second Goes
@cindex performance breakdown
@cindex prefill dominance

@subsection The codebud warm run (67.4 s) decomposed

@example
 67.4 s total wall-clock
 │
 ├─ 0.25 s  load check (Ollama confirms model is warm)
 │
 ├─ 57.19 s  PREFILL  ←── 84.9% of total time
 │            1,046 tokens processed at 18.3 tok/s
 │            The model reads the full planning prompt.
 │            Nothing can be shown to the user during this phase.
 │
 ├─  7.49 s  GENERATION
 │            62 tokens generated at 8.3 tok/s
 │            The JSON plan is produced here, token by token.
 │            The progress indicator shows the token counter.
 │
 └─  1.41 s  CODEBUD OVERHEAD
              Python startup, prompt build, HTTP, JSON parse,
              plan validation, step execution, memory write.
@end example

@noindent
@strong{Prefill is 84.9% of total time.}  Generation and all Codebud
overhead together account for less than 14% of the total.

@subsection The same breakdown for the short prompt (1.65 s)

@example
 1.65 s total (Ollama reported)
 │
 ├─ 0.15 s  load check
 ├─ 0.44 s  PREFILL   ←── 26.7% of total time (36 tokens at 81.8 tok/s)
 └─ 0.96 s  GENERATION  ←── 58.2% of total time (10 tokens at 10.4 tok/s)
@end example

@noindent
With a short prompt, generation dominates --- the model spends more time
producing output than reading input.  With the planning prompt, the ratio
inverts completely.

@subsection Why prefill is slower per token with a longer prompt

Prefill speed was @strong{81.8 tok/s} for 36 tokens but only
@strong{18.3 tok/s} for 1,046 tokens --- a 4.5× slowdown per token.

This is a direct consequence of the @dfn{self-attention} mechanism.
In each transformer layer, every token must attend to every other token.
The computation cost scales with the @emph{square} of sequence length:

@example
36-token prompt:   36 × 36  =  1,296 attention pairs per layer
1046-token prompt: 1046 × 1046 = 1,094,116 attention pairs per layer
                   = 844× more work

Ratio of prefill times: 57.19 / 0.44 = 130×
Expected ratio from token count alone: 1046 / 36 = 29×

The actual ratio is higher than linear (130× vs 29×) because attention
is super-linear, but lower than quadratic (844×) because the CPU can
parallelise some of the computation across its 8 threads.
@end example


@node Assessment
@section Assessment
@cindex assessment
@cindex optimisation directions
@cindex prompt length

@subsection What the numbers tell us

@enumerate

@item
@strong{The planning prompt is the dominant cost --- not model size, not
generation length, not tool overhead.}

57 out of 67 seconds (85%) are spent on prefill.  If you want to make
Codebud faster, reducing the planning prompt length is the highest-leverage
action.  Switching to a faster CPU or a faster disk has minimal effect
on a warm-model run.

@item
@strong{The pre-warmup eliminates cold-load penalty.}

Cold and warm runs are within 1 second of each other (68.3 s vs 67.4 s).
Without pre-warmup the cold run would take 78--98 s (add 10--30 s
cold-load).

@item
@strong{Codebud's Python overhead is 1.4 s --- negligible.}

The framework (AgentCore, planner, executor, safety checks, memory write)
adds under 2% to the total time.  This is not the bottleneck.

@item
@strong{The @command{llm} CLI baseline is not a fair competitor.}

@command{llm} sends 36 tokens; Codebud sends 1,046 tokens.  They are
doing different things.  A meaningful comparison would be: 9.6 s
(@command{llm}) vs 1.65 s (Ollama Test 2) are both ``raw model speed''
measurements.  The 65.6 s (Codebud) is the cost of structured JSON planning
on a CPU.

@end enumerate

@subsection Optimisation directions, ranked by expected impact

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .20 .45
@headitem Action @tab Expected saving @tab How
@item Reduce planning prompt to ~400 tokens @tab ~25--30 s @tab Remove examples, shorten rules, use terser tool descriptions
@item Switch to 7B model on GPU @tab ~55 s @tab GPU prefill is 10--50× faster; 57 s → 1--6 s
@item Use a dedicated small model for planning @tab ~40 s @tab A 1.5B model prefills ~2× faster
@item Cache the plan for repeated identical requests @tab ~65 s @tab Hash (user message + context); skip Ollama if cached
@item Reduce context window (@code{num_ctx}) @tab ~5--15 s @tab Smaller KV cache = faster prefill at cost of shorter memory
@end multitable

@noindent
@strong{None of the following will make a meaningful difference:}
reducing Python startup time, optimising JSON parsing, reducing HTTP
overhead, tuning generation parameters.  The bottleneck is purely prefill.

@subsection What ``beginner-friendly'' means here

If you are a new user wondering why Codebud takes a minute for a simple
request: @strong{the model is reading.}

Before it can write a single character of output, it must read and
process every character of the 1,046-token planning prompt --- the system
instructions, the tool list, the examples, your question.  On a CPU
without a dedicated GPU, this reading takes 57 seconds.  The answer
itself (62 tokens of JSON) then takes about 7 more seconds.

It is not a bug.  It is not a hang.  The progress spinner showing
``Thinking... 57s (prefill)'' is the model doing real work.


@node The Measurement Program
@section The Measurement Program
@cindex measurement program
@cindex benchmark script

The following self-contained Python script reproduces all four measurements.
Save it as @file{scripts/benchmark.py} and run it from the Codebud project
root with the model warm:

@example
#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
benchmark.py -- Measure Codebud planning prompt vs short prompt timing.

Usage (from Codebud project root, model must be running):
    export OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M
    python scripts/benchmark.py

Requires: requests (already in requirements.txt), agent package on PYTHONPATH.
"""
import json
import os
import sys
import time

import requests

# Ensure the agent package is importable
sys.path.insert(0, ".")

from agent.planner import LLMPlanner
from agent.safety import SafetyEngine
from agent.sandbox import Sandbox
from agent.tools.tool_registry import ToolRegistry

OLLAMA_BASE = os.environ.get("OLLAMA_BASE_URL", "http://localhost:11434")
MODEL = os.environ.get("OLLAMA_MODEL", "")
USER_PROMPT = "say hello in exactly 5 words"


def ollama_call(label: str, prompt: str) -> dict:
    """Send prompt to Ollama with stream=False and print timing."""
    print(f"\n@{'='*60@}")
    print(f"  TEST: @{label@}")
    print(f"  Prompt: @{len(prompt)@} chars, first 60: @{prompt[:60]!r@}")
    print("  Sending to Ollama (stream=False) ...")

    t0 = time.monotonic()
    r = requests.post(
        f"@{OLLAMA_BASE@}/api/generate",
        json=@{
            "model": MODEL,
            "prompt": prompt,
            "stream": False,
            "options": @{"temperature": 0@},
        @},
        timeout=(10, 600),
    )
    t1 = time.monotonic()
    data = r.json()
    wall = t1 - t0

    def ns(field):
        return data.get(field, 0)

    load_s  = ns("load_duration")        / 1e9
    pe_s    = ns("prompt_eval_duration") / 1e9
    e_s     = ns("eval_duration")        / 1e9
    total_s = ns("total_duration")       / 1e9
    pe_n    = data.get("prompt_eval_count", 0)
    e_n     = data.get("eval_count", 0)

    print(f"\n  Ollama timing (from API response):")
    print(f"    load_duration        : @{load_s:7.2f@} s")
    print(f"    prompt_eval_count    : @{pe_n:7d@} tokens")
    print(f"    prompt_eval_duration : @{pe_s:7.2f@} s  "
          f"(@{pe_n/pe_s:.1f@} tok/s)" if pe_s > 0 else "")
    print(f"    eval_count           : @{e_n:7d@} tokens")
    print(f"    eval_duration        : @{e_s:7.2f@} s  "
          f"(@{e_n/e_s:.1f@} tok/s)" if e_s > 0 else "")
    print(f"    total_duration       : @{total_s:7.2f@} s")
    print(f"    wall-clock           : @{wall:7.2f@} s")
    print(f"\n  Response (first 120 chars): @{data.get('response','')[:120]!r@}")
    return @{
        "label": label, "prompt_tokens": pe_n, "load_s": load_s,
        "prefill_s": pe_s, "gen_s": e_s, "gen_tokens": e_n,
        "total_s": total_s, "wall_s": wall,
    @}


def main():
    if not MODEL:
        print("ERROR: set OLLAMA_MODEL before running.")
        sys.exit(1)

    # Check Ollama is up
    try:
        requests.get(f"@{OLLAMA_BASE@}/api/tags", timeout=3).raise_for_status()
    except Exception as exc:
        print(f"ERROR: cannot reach Ollama at @{OLLAMA_BASE@}: @{exc@}")
        sys.exit(1)

    print(f"Model : @{MODEL@}")
    print(f"Ollama: @{OLLAMA_BASE@}")

    # Build the planning prompt
    sandbox  = Sandbox()
    registry = ToolRegistry(sandbox)
    safety   = SafetyEngine()
    planner  = LLMPlanner(registry, safety)
    planning_prompt = planner._build_prompt(USER_PROMPT)

    r1 = ollama_call("SHORT PROMPT (raw model baseline)", USER_PROMPT)
    r2 = ollama_call("PLANNING PROMPT (what Codebud sends)", planning_prompt)

    # Summary table
    print(f"\n@{'='*60@}")
    print("  SUMMARY")
    print(f"  @{'Test':<30@} @{'Tokens':>8@} @{'Prefill':>9@} @{'Gen':>7@} @{'Total':>8@}")
    print(f"  @{'-'*30@} @{'-'*8@} @{'-'*9@} @{'-'*7@} @{'-'*8@}")
    for r in [r1, r2]:
        print(f"  @{r['label']:<30@} @{r['prompt_tokens']:>8d@} "
              f"@{r['prefill_s']:>8.2f@}s @{r['gen_s']:>6.2f@}s "
              f"@{r['total_s']:>7.2f@}s")

    overhead_s = r2["prefill_s"] - r1["prefill_s"]
    token_diff = r2["prompt_tokens"] - r1["prompt_tokens"]
    print(f"\n  Extra tokens in planning prompt : @{token_diff@}")
    print(f"  Extra prefill time              : @{overhead_s:.2f@} s")
    print(f"  Prefill cost per extra token    : @{overhead_s/token_diff*1000:.1f@} ms/token")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
@end example

